      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the lifestyle like in Gaythorne?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Gaythorne offers a leafy, settled family lifestyle approximately eight kilometres north of the Brisbane CBD. The suburb is defined by quiet residential streets, character Queenslander homes, the Enoggera Creek greenway, and a genuine community feel that reflects its largely owner-occupier population. Mitchelton Station on the Ferny Grove line is accessible from the suburb, providing rail connections to the CBD, and the Blackwood Street precinct in adjacent Mitchelton provides everyday dining and retail amenity. It is a suburb where families come to stay, and that settled character is central to its enduring appeal." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is Gaythorne a good suburb to buy in right now?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Gaythorne offers genuine value for families comparing the northern Brisbane corridor. The suburb delivers the leafy character, school catchments, and Ferny Grove rail access of its better-known neighbours at a price point that reflects its position as one step removed from the tightest addresses in the corridor. For buyers who have compared Alderley and Mitchelton and found them beyond budget, Gaythorne's character homes, quiet streets, and established community make it a compelling long-term owner-occupier choice. Low stock turnover is a consistent feature, which means that buyers who identify Gaythorne as the right suburb often need to wait for the right property to appear." }
    }
  ]
